# What is Bigdata?
    Bernard Marr, the Analytics, KPI, AI, and BigData guru, defines BigData as the digital trace (or data) that we are generating in this digital era
    --> Big Data is all the data created from our daily digital activities — like using mobile apps, browsing the internet, making online transactions, using social media, or even data from sensors and devices.
    --> Every click, search, message, or transaction leaves behind data. When all this data is collected at a massive scale, it becomes Big Data.

# BigData Vs SmallData
 | Aspect     | BigData                          | SmallData                   |
 | Volume     | Massive(TBs-PBs)                 | Small(MBs-GBs)              |
 | Velocity   | High(real time/Streaming)        | Low(batch/manual updates)   |
 | Variety    | Structured+Unstructured          | Mostly Structured           |
 | Processing | Distributed(Spark, Hadoop)       | Single System(SQL, Python)  |
 | Storage    | Cloud/Data Lakes                 | Local DB/Enterprise Systems |
 | Use Case   | ML, analytics, real-time systems | reporting, dashboards       |

# BigData Life Cycle
    1. Data Collection
        Initiated based on a business problem or requirement
        Data comes from multiple sources (app, logs, APIs, sensors)
        --> If you don't collect the right data, everything downstream is useless. This step defines data quality, relevance, and business value from dayone.
![Data Collection](./Data%20Collection.png)

    2. Data Storage (HDFS / Data Lakes)
        Stored in distributed systems like Hadoop HDFS, S3, etc.
        --> Big Data can’t fit on a single machine. Distributed storage ensures:
            Scalability (handle TBs/PBs of data)
            Fault tolerance (no data loss if a node fails)
            Cost efficiency (commodity hardware / cloud storage)

    3. Data Processing & Modeling (MapReduce / ETL)
        Data is cleaned, transformed, and structured
        Data models define entities, relationships, and rules
        --> Raw data is messy. This step:
            Converts data into a usable structure
            Ensures consistency and integrity
            Makes data ready for querying and analytics
        --> Without modeling, you just have a data swamp.
![Data Modeling](./Data%20Modeling.png)

    4. Data Processing (Apache Spark, etc.)
        Advanced processing to extract insights
        Includes aggregations, joins, ML transformations
        --> This is where data turns into insights:
            Faster processing with distributed engines like Spark
            Enables real-time and batch analytics
            Supports machine learning and advanced analytics
![Data Processing](./Data%20Processing.png)

    5. Data Visualization
        Presented as dashboards, charts, reports
        --> No business user wants raw tables. Visualization:
            Makes insights easy to understand
            Helps stakeholders quickly identify trends
            Bridges the gap between data and decision-makers
![Data Visualization](./Data%20Visualization.png)

    6. Decision Making & Feedback Loop
        Insights drive business decisions
        New requirements generate more data
        --> This closes the loop:
            Data becomes actionable value
            Drives new use cases and improvements
            Keeps the system evolving (continuous lifecycle)

# Characteristics of BigData
    1. Volume
        Refers to massive amounts of data(TBs-->PBs-->beyond)
        Comes from logs, transactions, social media, IoT, etc.
        --> Traditional systems cannot scale
            Requires distributed storage (HDFS, S3)

    2. Velocity
        Data is generated and processed at high speed
        Includes real-time/Streaming data
        --> Needs stream processing systems like kafka, Spark Streaming/Flink
            Enables real-time decision making

    3. Variety
        Data comes in multiple formats
           Structured (tables)
           Semi-structured (JSON, XML)
           Unstructured (images, videos, logs)
           --> Requires flexible schema design (schema-on-read, )
           Supports diverse data source
  
 # Additional Characteristics
    4. Veracity
        Veracity is about the accuracy, reliability, and trustworthiness of data. Since data comes from multiple sources, it may contain inconsistencies or errors.
        --> Poor-quality data leads to incorrect insights, so strong data validation, cleansing, and ETL processes are essential.

    5. Value
       Value is the ultimate goal of Big Data — turning data into meaningful insights that drive smarter decisions and business outcomes.
       --> Without value, data is just stored information. The real benefit comes from using it to improve efficiency, innovation, and decision-making.

# Bit, Bytes and Beyond
    Data is measured starting from the smallest unit called bit, which represents a binary value of 0 or 1
    Eight bits make one byte, and from there the size increase exponentially into kilobytes, megabytes, gigabytes, and terabytes-the range most everyday systems operate in.
    BigData goes far beyond this, reaching scales like petabytes, exabytes, zettabytes, and even yottabytes
    To put that into perspective, a single exabyte can store millions of high-resolution 4k movies, while a zettabyte equals a billion terabytes.
    This massive growth in data volume makes it impossible to rely on traditional storage and processing systems, which is why distributed architectures and cloud-based solutions are essential for handling BigData efficiently
